# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dkb-group
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dkb-group/asano-zaibatsu] Asano Sōichirō 浅野総一郎 founded Asano zaibatsu in 1884 after purchasing the Fukagawa Cement Works from the government with support from Shibusawa Eiichi 渋沢栄一 of the Shibusawa zaibatsu.
[src:dkb-group/asano-zaibatsu] Because the Asano zaibatsu had no bank of its own it relied on Shibusawa and Yasuda zaibatsu capital, but it was still "the fifth-largest" zaibatsu in Japan.
[src:dkb-group/asano-zaibatsu] It had 64 affiliated companies in 1940 and 94 in 1943.
[src:dkb-group/asano-zaibatsu] It almost monopolized the cement industry in Japan.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] A **corporate group**, **company group** or **business group**, also formally known as a **group of companies**, is a collection of parent and subsidiary corporations that function as a single economic entity through a common source of control.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] These types of groups are often managed by an account manager.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] The concept of a group is frequently used in tax law and accounting and (less frequently) company law to attribute the rights and duties of one member of the group to another or the whole.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] If the corporations are engaged in entirely different businesses, the group is called a conglomerate.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] The forming of corporate groups usually involves consolidation via mergers and acquisitions, although the group concept focuses on the instances in which the merged and acquired corporate entities remain in existence rather than the instances in which they are dissolved by the parent.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] The group may be owned by a holding company which may have no actual operations.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] A corporate group is composed of companies.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] The general rule is that a company is a separate legal entity from its shareholders, that is the shareholder's liability for the subsidiary's debts is limited to the value of the shares, and the shareholders cannot be required to perform the company's obligations.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] However, some jurisdictions create exceptions to this rule.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] For example, Germany has created affiliated enterprise law which provides situations in which one company is liable for the debts of another company.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] In New Zealand, the Companies Act provides that the assets of related companies may be pooled to pay the creditors if one of the companies is liquidated.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] However, the circumstances in which this power will be exercised are very narrow.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Leff defines "business group" as a group of companies that does business in different markets under common administrative or financial control whose members are linked by relations of interpersonal trust on the basis of similar personal ethnic or commercial background.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] One method of defining a group is as a cluster of legally distinct firms with a managerial relationship.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] The relationship between the firms in a group may be formal or informal.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] A keiretsu is one type of business group.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Douma and Schreuder (2013) distinguish "horizontal" and "vertical business groups" as follows: 'Business groups can be horizontal or vertical as far as their structure is concerned.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] In a horizontal business group there is no central holding company – the group companies are connected through various formal or informal ties, including reciprocal shareholding.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Thus, a horizontal business group is a rather loose confederation of firms.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Coordination between them is achieved mainly by mutual adjustment and standardization of norms.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Mitsubishi is a well-known example of a horizontal business group as are many other keiretsu.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Chinese groups exhibit similar features.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Horizontal business groups are also referred to as "associative business groups".
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] A vertical business group is a group of companies controlled, but not entirely owned, by a single investor.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Vertical groups are often organized as pyramids of companies controlled by the main investor through a holding company.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] A unique feature of pyramidal holdings is that it allows the main investor to exert control with a limited amount of capital.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Korean chaebols, Indian business houses and most European business groups are vertical in character.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Vertical business groups are also referred to as "hierarchical business groups".
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Encarnation refers to Indian business houses, emphasizing multiple forms of ties among group members.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Powell and Smith-Doerr state that a business group is a network of firms that regularly collaborate over a long time period.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Granovetter argues that business groups refers to an intermediate level of binding, excluding on the one hand a set of firms bound merely by short-term alliances and on the other a set of firms legally consolidated into a single unit.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Williamson claims that business groups lie between markets and hierarchies; this is further worked out by Douma & Schreuder.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Khanna and Rivkin suggest that business groups are typically not legal constructs though some regulatory bodies have attempted to codify a definition.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] In the United Arab Emirates, a business group can also be known as a trade association.
[src:dkb-group/corporate-group] Typical examples are Adidas Group or Icelandair Group.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] In 2000, DKB merged with Fuji Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan to form Mizuho Financial Group.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] In 2002, DKB's corporate & investment banking division was transferred to Mizuho Corporate Bank, while its retail banking division was transferred to Mizuho Bank.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] In 1971, Dai-ichi Bank and Nippon Kangyo Bank merged to form DKB, which instantly surpassed longtime leader the Fuji Bank as the largest Japanese bank measured by assets and deposit market share.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] DKB formed the core of the DKB Group (or Dai-Ichi Kangyo Group), the largest Japanese keiretsu in terms of the number of associated companies, and became the central bank of DKB Group.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Taking over Nippon Kangyo and Noko's operation, DKB was the sole trustee of the Takarakuji lottery and was the only bank to have branches in every prefecture in Japan.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] DKB executives worried about the recurrence of the problem in their Teikoku Bank period when the two former banks' employees were on bad terms with each other.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Therefore, they were particular about "a merger of equals." DKB's board of directors, for example, was always composed half-and-half of the former Dai-ichi members and former NKB members.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] The board of directors installed the former two banks members alternately as the next chairperson and president.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] These practices backfired however, only causing difficulty among the employees similar to Teikoku Bank's case.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Irrational personnel affairs prevented DKB from increasing revenue and profit.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Although DKB had more assets than any other Japanese bank, its capabilities were inferior to high-performing banks such as Fuji, Sumitomo, Sanwa or Mitsubishi.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] During the Japanese asset price bubble of the late 1980s, Japanese banks, including DKB, granted increasingly risky loans.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Even worse, DKB financed not only high-risk companies but also yakuza, in order to invest in capital resources more easily than its competitors.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Furthermore, loans to sōkaiya (corporate racketeers) amounted to 30 billion JPY.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] After the bubble's collapse, these bad loans were judged to be poor value for money.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] A raid by Tokyo prosecutors in 1997 impeaching of the loans to sōkaiya laid DKB open to public criticism.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] Kuniji Miyazaki (宮崎 邦次, *Miyazaki Kuniji*; 1930–1997), former president and then chairperson of DKB, who faced severe pressure over a series of alleged misdeeds, committed suicide by hanging himself in his home.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] DKB combined with Fuji Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan in 2000, forming Mizuho Financial Group.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] In 2002, DKB's corporate & investment banking division was transferred to Mizuho Corporate Bank and its retail banking division to Mizuho Bank respectively.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] The Dai-Ichi Kangyo name remains in use by a Shinjuku, Tokyo-based credit union, **Dai-Ichi Kangyo Credit Cooperative** (第一勧業信用組合), which was founded as a credit union for Nippon Kangyo Bank employees during the Taisho era.
[src:dkb-group/dai-ichi-kangyo-bank] It remains active in the Tokyo region with over 45,000 members, and uses a modified version of the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank branding.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] (DSI) began operating in the U.S. in 2006.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] It is the U.S. subsidiary of Daiichi Sankyo Company, Limited, and a member of the Daiichi Sankyo Group.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] The organization, which includes U.S. commercial operations and global clinical development (Daiichi Sankyo Pharma Development), is headquartered in Basking Ridge, New Jersey.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo Europe, GmbH (DSE), the European subsidiary, is headquartered in Munich, Germany.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] The organization is responsible for development and manufacturing for 12 European countries.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo Company, Limited is a full member of the European Federation of Pharmaceutical Industries and Associations (EFPIA) and of the International Federation of Pharmaceutical Manufacturers and Associations (IFPMA).
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo was established in 2005 through the merger of Sankyo Company, Limited (三共株式会社, *Sankyō Kabushiki Kaisha*) and Daiichi Pharmaceutical Company, Limited (第一製薬株式会社, *Daiichi Seiyaku Kabushiki Kaisha*), which were century-old pharmaceutical companies based in Japan.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Sankyo Co., Ltd. was founded by Jokichi Takamine, who patented the isolation of adrenaline.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Takamine was president of Sankyo Co., Ltd from March 1913 until July 1922.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] In 1990, Sankyo acquired the German Luitpold-Werk Group, a pharmaceutical company based in Munich.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] In 2019, Luitpold renamed itself after its American Regent brand.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] American Regent, now based in the United States, is a subsidiary of Daiichi Sankyo.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] In 2006, Daiichi Sankyo acquired Zepharma, the OTC drugs unit of Astellas Pharma.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] On June 10, 2008, the company agreed to take a majority (64%) stake in Indian generic drug maker Ranbaxy, with a deal valued at about $4.6 billion.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] It acquired U3 Pharma in June 2008, contributing a therapeutic anti-HER3 antibody to the company's anticancer portfolio.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo is retaining US co-promotion right of the (Roche licensed) drug.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] The shutdown of Plexxikon was announced in 2022 as Daiichi Sankyo pivots to focus on more antibody-drug conjugate therapies.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] On April 7, 2014, Daiichi Sankyo announced it had agreed to vote its shares in Ranbaxy in favor of Sun Pharma's acquisition of 100% of Ranbaxy through the merger process which entailed a share swap.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] On September 29, 2014, Daiichi Sankyo agreed to acquire Ambit Biosciences for approximately $410 million, the deal enabled Daiichi to gain the cancer compound quizartinib.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] On April 20, 2015, the company announced it had sold off the 8.9% stake in Sun Pharmaceutical Industries it acquired when acquiring Ranbaxy, raising $3.2 billion.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] It transferred 41 of its products in Japan to Alfresa Holdings Corporation for JPY 4.2 billion in 2018 in order to focus on oncology.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] The company acquired ramosetron, nicardipine and barnidipine from Astellas Pharma in October 2019.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] In January 2020, the company's market value rose above JPY 5 trillion after the U.S.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Food and Drug Administration approval and release of Enhertu, an antibody-drug conjugate for cancer treatment.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo developed Enhertu in cooperation with AstraZeneca, which agreed in March 2019 to pay up to $6.9 billion to Daiichi Sankyo in exchange for a share of Enhertu's sales.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] As of 2015, Daiichi Sankyo was being "closely monitored" after settling charges concerning payment of remuneration to physicians in the form of speaker fees as part of company's Physician Organization and Discussion program, in violation of the False Claims Act, an anti-kickback statute.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Daiichi Sankyo agreed to pay the United States and state Medicaid programs $39 million to settle allegations by the United States Department of Justice over kickbacks to doctors.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] As part of the company's Physician Organization and Discussion program which ran from 2005 through 2011, Daiichi Sankyo paid physicians improper kickbacks in the form of speaker fees to induce physicians to prescribe Daiichi Sankyo's drugs, including Azor, Benicar, Tribenzor and Welchol.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] "Schemes such as this are particularly abhorrent," said Inspector General Daniel R.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] "Manufacturers and physicians who engage in them are cheating Medicare and Medicaid out of millions of dollars and threatening programs upon which many elderly and disabled Americans rely.
[src:dkb-group/daiichi-sankyo-co] My office will take whatever steps necessary to guard against improper alliances between manufacturers of drugs and those who prescribe them.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 2018, Dentsu announced its reorganization into a holding company and as a result, most of the company's functions (including its advertising business) moved to a new company under the Dentsu name and the existing company rebranding to the Dentsu Group, the changes took effect by January 1, 2020.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu was originally established as **Japan Advertising Ltd.** (日本広告株式会社, *Nihon Kōkoku Kabushiki-gaisha*) and **Telegraphic Service Co.** (電報通信社, *Denpō Tsūshin-sha*) by Hoshiro Mitsunaga.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 1906, Telegraphic Service Co. became **Japan Telegraphic Communication Co., Ltd.** (株式会社日本電報通信社, *Kabushiki-gaisha Nihon Denpō Tsūshin-sha*).
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The next year, Japan Advertising Ltd. merged with Japan Telegraphic Communication Co., Ltd. to create advertising and communications operations.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Japan Telegraphic Communication Co., Ltd. sold off its news division to Doumei News Agency in 1936 to change the company's focus to specialized advertising.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 1943, 16 companies were acquired in order to supplement Japan Telegraphic's advertising business.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] That same year, operational bases were established in Tokyo, Osaka, Nagoya, and Kyūshū.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] With the 1951 arrival of commercial radio broadcasting in Japan, the Radio Division was established at Japan Telegraphic's head and local offices.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 1955, Japan Telegraphic Communication Co., Ltd. changed its name to **Dentsu Inc.** 1995 saw Dentsu creating five domestic regional subsidiaries.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] On December 10, 2018, Dentsu announced its intention to restructure into a holding company which would form another company under the Dentsu name handling its advertising and production divisions.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu was listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange in 2001.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] During the initial public offering of Dentsu, in December 2001, a trader at UBS Warburg, the Swiss investment bank, sent an order to sell 610,000 shares in this company at ¥6 each, while he intended to sell 16 shares at ¥600,000.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu's sales are more than double its nearest competitor, Hakuhodo or ADK, in the Japanese market, thanks to the company's origins as a media representative during the early part of the 20th century, producing the first newspaper advertisements as well as the first television commercials in Japan.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In July 2003, Dentsu acquired Pioneer LDC from Pioneer Corporation and renamed it to Geneon Entertainment, while its North American division, Pioneer Entertainment, was renamed to Geneon USA.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] On November 12, 2008, Dentsu announced that it was selling 80.1% of its ownership in Geneon to NBCUniversal's Universal Pictures International Entertainment (UPI), who planned to merge the company with its Universal Pictures Japan division to form a new company.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] On 12 July 2012, Dentsu agreed to acquire British-based Aegis Group plc in a cash deal worth $4.9 billion.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu Aegis Network, managed all Aegis Media work and non-Japanese Dentsu operations worldwide.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In September 2020 Dentsu Group Inc. announced that its international business Dentsu Aegis Network will operate under the dentsu brand.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] This simplification has seen three lines of business established across media, customer relationship management, and creative.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The business is registered as Dentsu International Limited with UK Companies House in October 2020.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In April 2015, Dentsu announced the launch of a corporate venture capital fund, Dentsu Ventures, to provide companies across the U.S., Europe, and Asia with capital and business support.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In the same month, Dentsu Ventures Global Fund I was launched with a total capital of five billion yen.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In May 2021, Dentsu Ventures Global Fund II was launched with a total capital of ten billion yen.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu Ventures investments include Cheddar, Clear Labs, Exo, GRAIL, Overtime, OpenWeb, Survios, Twist Bioscience, Tynker, and Upside Foods.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In July 2023, Dentsu announced that it had founded its own anime business, Dentsu Anime Solutions, to boost its presence in the anime industry.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In August 2023, it was announced Dentsu had acquired the Berlin-headquartered digital-first brand, communications and creative agency, RCKT.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The RCKT brand would be retained during a period of integration, becoming known as “RCKT, a Dentsu Creative Company”.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 2018 Dentsu acquired GlobalMind, a LATAM based digital first agency based out of Argentina and Miami, USA.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] GlobalMind was the #1 independent media agency in LATAM owner of iColic, a creative agency which helped GlobalMind on the endeavour of conquering Latin America.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Andy Berman and Marcelo Montefiore were the co-CEOs of The agency until they sold it to Dentsu.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu Inc. categorises project markets in four different parts: National advertisement market; Advertisement-related market; New market; Foreign market (in addition to Dentsu Aegis Network, its overseas subsidiary, which operates in over 120 countries).
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] National advertisement market consists of media projects.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Advertisement related projects consist of marketing services.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] New market consists of sport events advertisement.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Foreign market contains above mentioned three categories in the foreign market.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The Dentsu Building is a high-rise building in Shiodome, Minato, Tokyo, which houses Dentsu's corporate offices.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] With 48 floors that rise to 213.34 m (700 ft), it is the eleventh-tallest building in Tokyo.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] It was designed by Jean Nouvel, the French architect, and completed in 2002.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] It was built over the site of Tokyo's first railway station, and sits aside the Hamarikyu Gardens, formerly the site of a shōgun's vacation home.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Since 1925, Dentsu employees have had a company tradition of climbing Mount Fuji.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Every July all new staff and newly promoted executives climb Mt Fuji.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Employees who are not physically able to do so are exempt.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] A former employee gave the reasoning behind this as: "The message is: 'We are going to conquer the one symbol that represents Japan more than anything else.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In August 2015, Dentsu was caught exceeding its own 70-hour monthly maximum overtime limit.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In December, Matsuri Takahashi, a University of Tokyo graduate and 24-year-old female employee of Dentsu, committed suicide.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The Japanese government recognized her suicide as karoshi, a Japanese term for death from overworking.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In July 2017, the company was charged by Japanese authorities for the death of Takahashi.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] No individuals were charged, only the corporation.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The company admitted allowing illegal levels of overtime and was convicted in October, paying ¥500,000 in fines.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Tadashi Ishii, Representative Director and President & CEO, notified Dentsu on December 28, 2016 that he will resign as Representative Director and President & CEO.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] His papers were sent to the prosecutors office because of the violation of the Labor Standards Act.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] A 2017 attempt to encourage letting workers "leave the office at 3 p.m. on the last Friday of the month" did not get much participation.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Also in 2017, a former executive creative director of Dentsu Japan has resigned from his own company following allegations he sexually harassed a woman during his tenure at the advertising giant.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Before the later bribery and bid-rigging cases, Dentsu was also scrutinized for its role in Tokyo's successful bid for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 2020, Reuters reported that Haruyuki Takahashi, a former Dentsu executive who later joined the Tokyo 2020 organising committee board, had received more than US$8 million from the Tokyo bid committee for undisclosed activities.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Takahashi told Reuters that his work included lobbying IOC members, including former athletics official Lamine Diack, and that he had given gifts such as a Seiko watch and digital cameras.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] IOC president Thomas Bach later said that the IOC had received confirmation that the payments did not infringe IOC rules.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In 2022, a former executive at Dentsu was arrested on suspicion of receiving bribes from sponsors of the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] In February 2023, Japan's competition regulator filed criminal complaints against six firms, including Dentsu, over alleged bid rigging of contracts for the games.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The companies were charged under anti-monopoly law and accused of lowering the competitiveness of their tenders.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The case also saw the arrest of a senior Olympic official from Japan and the head of Dentsu's sports division.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] The corruption scandal has clouded the chance of landing the 2030 Winter Olympics by the city of Sapporo, an early favorite.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] According to one media report, Dentsu does business with almost every major institution in Japan, accounting for about 28 percent of the national advertising budget.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Its connections to the government are so tight that *The New York Times* referred to Dentsu as "the unofficial communications department of the governing Liberal Democratic Party", and it has also been likened to the CIA on account of its reach.
[src:dkb-group/dentsu] Dentsu played a major role as a management company during Roki Sasaki's MLB team selection process that resulted in his signing with the Dodgers in 2025.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The **DKB Group** (第一勧銀グループ, *Dai'ichi Kangin Gurūpu*) or the **Dai-Ichi Kangyo Group** was the largest Japanese keiretsu in the late 1990s.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The group emerged after World War II and coalesced around the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] Two of DKB's largest clients, Kawasaki Heavy Industries and Furukawa Electric, led their own respective corporate groups with a cross-supply relationship between the two.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The Kawasaki and Furukawa groups agreed to begin holding presidents' meetings in 1966.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] Itochu, which historically supplied Kawasaki with raw materials, became the main general trading company for the combined group.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The group's presidents began regular Sankin-kai (三金会) meetings in 1971.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] Also in that year, the group's name developed from the merger of Dai-Ichi Bank and Nippon Kangyo Bank.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] In 1998, an announcement was made that the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank was to be merged with Fuji Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan to form Mizuho Financial Group.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The resulting group, which was established in September 2000, was the largest banking group in the world with assets of 140 trillion yen.
[src:dkb-group/dkb-group] The next few years saw a parallel consolidation of their keiretsu industrial partners and saw the group grow to 150 trillion yen in assets (30% GDP).
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The **Yasuda Bank** (Japanese: 安田銀行) from 1880 to 1948, then **Fuji Bank** (富士銀行) from 1948 to 2000, was one of the largest Japanese banks for much of the 20th century, together with Dai-Ichi Bank, Mitsubishi Bank, Mitsui Bank, and Sumitomo Bank.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] It was the main bank of the Yasuda zaibatsu until World War II, and afterwards of the Fuyo Group.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] By 1988 at the height of the Japanese asset price bubble, it had become the world's third-largest bank by total assets.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The Fuji Bank combined with Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan in 2000 to form Mizuho Financial Group, and changed its name to Mizuho Corporate Bank in 2002 after transferring its retail banking operations to Mizuho Bank.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The bank traces its history back to the old Yasuda zaibatsu.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Zenjiro Yasuda, a migrant from Toyama, opened a dry goods store in the Nihonbashi area of Edo in 1864, known as *Yasuda-ya* (lit.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] After the Meiji Restoration in 1869, the company underwrote bonds for the Japanese government, whose credit standing was low then, and financed many public works such as railroads, harbor constructions, and so forth.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The company was incorporated in 1880 with a share capital of 10 million yen.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] In 1912, Yasuda-ya was incorporated and renamed Yasuda Bank, in a process where Yasuda absorbed the assets and business of seventeen different Japanese banking institutions.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] In the Taishō period, the Japanese banking community was thrown into financial difficulties because of World War I and the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] In the immediate wake of the earthquake, Yasuda absorbed ten smaller regional banks which lacked a sufficient financial base to cover their deposits.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] This merger made Yasuda Bank the largest in Japan by several measures, with share capital of 150 million yen, deposits of 542 million yen, loans of 521 million yen, 211 branches and 3,700 employees.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The Yasuda Bank's activity remained entirely domestic.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Following World War II, the Yasuda zaibatsu was dissolved by the Supreme Commander of the Allied Powers.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] On October 1, 1948, Yasuda Bank changed its name to Fuji Bank, named after Mount Fuji.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji formed the Fuyo Group, one of the largest *keiretsu*, together with other former Yasuda zaibatsu companies.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] As the Japanese economy was rebuilt after the war, Fuji Bank expanded its business in syndicated lending, corporate banking, public money management, mortgages and retail financial services.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] It worked with other major banks as partners when it was at risk of over-extending its funds.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] However, the formation of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank (DKB) in 1971 dethroned Fuji from its top status in the Japanese banking industry.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] In an attempt to restore its preeminence, Fuji agreed to merge with Osaka-based Sanwa Bank in the late 1970s, but failed to win approval from the Ministry of Finance.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Sumitomo Bank also rose as an intense competitor to Fuji in the 1980s, and both banks aggressively courted similar corporate banking clients, growing their loan portfolios dramatically with what would later become non-performing loans.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji Capital Markets Corp. was founded in New York in 1990 going on to become one of the lead players in the swaps market.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] FCMC went on to open offices in London in 1992 and Hong Kong in 1994 which still exist as Mizuho Capital Markets Corp.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] FCMC was one of the first Japanese Banks to connect to the internet, registering the fcmc.com domain in 1993.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] However, following the collapse of the Japanese asset price bubble in the early 1990s, Fuji and other Japanese banks were increasingly troubled by bad loans and inadequate back-office systems.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji attempted to diversify its domestic services, establishing Fuji Securities and Fuji Trust & Banking Co. in 1994, but neither subsidiary was able to make substantial profits.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] On November 24, 1997, Yamaichi, Fuji Bank's affiliated securities firm, announced it would cease operations and was declared bankrupt by the Tokyo District Court.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji's inability to support Yamaichi led to a rapid fall in Fuji's stock price on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Between 1998 and 2000, Fuji laid off thousands of employees and borrowed one trillion yen of public funds.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Yasuda Trust & Banking, Fuji's affiliated trust company, entered severe financial difficulties in 1999 and sought an additional capital injection from Fuji.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji was still experiencing its own difficulties and could not afford to rescue Yasuda.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] However, Fuji and DKB were able to negotiate a three-party transaction in which Fuji and DKB merged their respective trust banks, and the merged company acquired the corporate and pension divisions of Yasuda Trust & Banking.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] On September 29, 2000, all shares of Fuji, DKB and the Industrial Bank of Japan were acquired by a newly formed Mizuho Holdings.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The three banks continued to operate separately pending their final legal merger.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] At the time of the September 11 attacks on New York's World Trade Center, Fuji Bank's United States offices were located at the impact zone of United Airlines Flight 175 in 2 World Trade Center (the South Tower) occupying the office space on the 79th through 82nd floors.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] After the North Tower was hit, the managers rushed to evacuate their employees.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Within fifteen minutes, the managers had successfully evacuated 120 employees.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] However, 23 Fuji Bank employees died in the attack.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Fuji Bank employee Stanley Praimnath was one of only eighteen remaining people located at the South Tower's collision zone to survive.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] DKB's offices were located in the North Tower.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] On April 1, 2002, Fuji acquired the corporate banking operations of DKB and absorbed all operations of IBJ, renaming itself Mizuho Corporate Bank.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] DKB simultaneously acquired the individual banking operations of Fuji and renamed itself Mizuho Bank.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] Both banks became wholly owned subsidiaries of Mizuho Financial Group.
[src:dkb-group/fuji-bank] The legal merger of Mizuho Corporate Bank with Mizuho Bank took place on July 1, 2013.
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] Fujita was founded by Densaburo Fujita, who created a *zaibatsu* (pre-war conglomerate) by producing military goods during the Satsuma Rebellion and rapidly expanded his business to construction, mining, and other businesses.
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] After World War II, the Allied Occupation authorities broke up the zaibatsu conglomerates.
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] Many of the assets of the Fujita zaibatsu were placed in the custody of Fujita Kankō, a resort development company.
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] This has since become the central body of the Fuhita *keiretsu* (post-war conglomerate).
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] The construction of the third terminal of Shahjalal International Airport of Dhaka will be carried out by Aviation Dhaka Consortium (ADC), consisting of Mitsubishi Corporation, Samsung C&T Corporation and Fujita.
[src:dkb-group/fujita-company] The total cost of the project is ৳213 billion (US$1.7 billion).
